Notes on screening by bulk ﬂows

We will consider hydrodynamics on a static membrane tube (i.e. we assume that the cylindrical geometry is stable to perturbations in shape). In the limit of small inertia the 3D velocity ﬁeld, u, satisﬁes the continuity and Stokes equations

∇ · u = 0; η∇2u = ∇P

(S76)

where P is the pressure and η the viscosity. This is coupled to the membrane velocity at the boundary with a no-slip condition.
Stress balance at the membrane is imposed by the 2D continuity and Stokes equations and, for surfaces of zero Gaussian curvature, can be written as

∇ivi = 0; ηm∆LBvi − ∇iσ = t+i + t−i

(S77)

where ηm is the (2D) membrane viscosity, σ is the surface tension, v = viei is the tangential membrane velocity and
∆LB is the Laplace-Beltrami operator (formally this corresponds to ∆LB = δd where d is the exterior derivative and
δ is the co-diﬀerential). The combined operator δd is the generalization of the curl-curl operator to a manifold and acts like a Laplacian [7, 10]. The symbols t±i are the traction forces from the bulk ﬂuid acting on the membrane (± denoting interior and exterior respectively)[3, 7].

